            "size": 30074,
            "text": "{\"search_results\":[{\"content\":\"## 3\\\\. Your First Generic React Component\\n\\nLet's convert a simple component to use generics. Here's a basic list component:\\n\\n```\\n// Non-generic version\\ninterface User {\\n  id: number;\\n  name: string;\\n  email: string;\\n}\\n\\ninterface UserListProps {\\n  users: User[];\\n  onUserSelect: (user: User) =\\u003e void;\\n}\\n\\nfunction UserList({ users, onUserSelect }: UserListProps) {\\n  return (\\n    \\u003cul\\u003e\\n      {users.map(user =\\u003e (\\n        \\u003cli key={user.id} onClick={() =\\u003e onUserSelect(user)}\\u003e\\n          {user.name}\\n        \\u003c/li\\u003e\\n      ))}\\n    \\u003c/ul\\u003e\\n  );\\n}\\n\\n```\\n\\nEnter fullscreen modeExit fullscreen mode\\n\\nNow let's make it generic:\\n\\n```\\n// Generic version\\ninterface ListItem {\\n  id: number | string;\\n}\\n\\ninterface GenericListProps\\u003cT extends ListItem\\u003e {\\n  items: T[];\\n  onItemSelect: (item: T) =\\u003e void;\\n  renderItem: (item: T) =\\u003e React.ReactNode;\\n}\\n\\nfunction GenericList\\u003cT extends ListItem\\u003e({\\n  items,\\n  onItemSelect,\\n  renderItem\\n}: GenericListProps\\u003cT\\u003e) {\\n  return (\\n    \\u003cul\\u003e\\n      {items.map(item =\\u003e (\\n        \\u003cli key={item.id} onClick={() =\\u003e onItemSelect(item)}\\u003e\\n          {renderItem(item)}\\n        \\u003c/li\\u003e\\n      ))}\\n    \\u003c/ul\\u003e\\n  );\\n}\\n\\n```\\n\\nEnter fullscreen modeExit fullscreen mode\\n\\n**Use generics:**\\n\\n```\\n// Usage with explicit type\\n\\u003cGenericList\\u003cUser\\u003e\\n  items={users}\\n  onItemSelect={handleUserSelect}\\n  renderItem={(user) =\\u003e user.name}\\n/\\u003e\\n\\n// TypeScript can often infer the type\\n\\u003cGenericList\\n  items={products} // TypeScript infers Product[]\\n  onItemSelect={handleProductSelect}\\n  renderItem={(product) =\\u003e product.title}\\n/\\u003e\\n\\n```\\n\\nEnter fullscreen modeExit fullscreen mode\\n\\n**Props interface with generic types** ensures type safety throughout the component. The `T extends ListItem` constraint ensures all items have an `id` property for the `key` prop.## 7\\\\. Generic Hooks and Custom Logic\\n\\n**Creating generic custom hooks:**\\n\\n```\\nfunction useLocalStorage\\u003cT\\u003e(key: string, initialValue: T) {\\n  const [storedValue, setStoredValue] = useState\\u003cT\\u003e(() =\\u003e {\\n    try {\\n      const item = window.localStorage.getItem(key);\\n      return item ? JSON.parse(item) : initialValue;\\n    } catch (error) {\\n      return initialValue;\\n    }\\n  });\\n\\n  const setValue = (value: T | ((val: T) =\\u003e T)) =\\u003e {\\n    try {\\n      const valueToStore = value instanceof Function ? value(storedValue) : value;\\n      setStoredValue(valueToStore);\\n      window.localStorage.setItem(key, JSON.stringify(valueToStore));\\n    } catch (error) {\\n      console.error(error);\\n    }\\n  };\\n\\n  return [storedValue, setValue] as const;\\n}\\n\\n// Usage in component\\nfunction UserPreferences() {\\n  const [preferences, setPreferences] = useLocalStorage\\u003cUserPrefs\\u003e('userPrefs', {\\n    theme: 'light',\\n    language: 'en'\\n  });\\n}\\n\\n```\\n\\nEnter fullscreen modeExit fullscreen mode\\n\\n**Combining generic components with generic hooks:**\",\"date\":\"2025-06-08\",\"icon\":\"https://kimi-web-img.moonshot.cn/prod-data/icon-cache-img/dev.to\",\"mime\":\"\",\"site_name\":\"DEV Community\",\"snippet\":\"TypeScript generics in React components provide a powerful way to create reusable, type-safe components that work with different data types ...Read more\",\"title\":\"TypeScript Generics in React Components: A Complete Guide\",\"url\":\"https://dev.to/jonathanguo/typescript-generics-in-react-components-a-complete-guide-1e88\"},{\"content\":\"Have you ever found yourself writing duplicate code to handle different data types? Or worse, resorting to using `any` and losing all the benefits of TypeScript's type checking? If so, generics are about to become your new best friend.\\n\\nIn this tutorial, I'll show you how to use generics in TypeScript to write reusable, type-safe code. I'll cover everything from basic usage in functions to more complex scenarios with interfaces and classes.\\n\\n## What are Generics?\\n\\nGenerics are essentially parameterized types - they allow you to provide the type to a function, interface, or class as a parameter. This means you can write a single implementation that works with a variety of types while maintaining full type safety.\\n\\nWithout generics, you'd have two options:\\n\\n1.  Use specific types and duplicate code for each type\\n\\n2.  Use `any` and lose type safety\\n\\nNeither solution is ideal. Let's see how generics solve this problem.\",\"date\":\"2025-05-17\",\"icon\":\"https://kimi-web-img.moonshot.cn/prod-data/icon-cache-img/nicolahibbert.com\",\"mime\":\"\",\"site_name\":\"nicolahibbert.com\",\"snippet\":\"Have you ever found yourself writing duplicate code to handle different data types? Or worse, resorting to using `any` and losing all the benefits of TypeScript's type checking? If so, generics are about to become your new best friend.\\n\\nIn this tutorial, I'll show you how to use generics in TypeScript to write reusable, type-safe code. I'll cover everything from basic usage in functions to more complex scenarios with interfaces and classes.\\n\\n What are Generics?\\n\\nGenerics are essentially parameterized types - they allow you to provide the type to a function, interface, or class as a parameter. This means you can write a single implementation that works with a variety of types while maintaining full type safety.\\n\\nWithout generics, you'd have two options:\\n\\n1.  Use specific types and duplicate code for each type\\n\\n2.  Use `any` and lose type safety\\n\\nNeither solution is ideal. Let's see how generics solve this problem.\",\"title\":\"TypeScript Generics: A Practical Guide\",\"url\":\"https://nicolahibbert.com/typescript-generics-a-practical-guide/\"},{\"content\":\"**Introduction**\\n\\nTypeScript is a powerful programming language that has gained immense popularity in recent years. One of the key features that sets it apart from other languages is its support for generics. Generics allow developers to create reusable code that can work with multiple data types, making it an essential tool for any serious TypeScript developer. In this tutorial, we will delve into the world of TypeScript generics, exploring their benefits, implementation, and best practices.\\n\\n**What You Will Learn**\\n\\nIn this tutorial, you will learn:\\n\\n-  The basics of TypeScript generics and how they work\\n\\n-  How to implement generics in TypeScript\\n\\n-  Advanced usage of generics, including type inference and constraints\\n\\n-  Best practices for using generics, including performance and security considerations\\n\\n-  How to test and debug generic code\\n\\n-  Common mistakes to avoid when using generics\\n\\n**Prerequisites**\\n\\n-  Basic knowledge of TypeScript and object-oriented programming\\n\\n-  Familiarity with TypeScript type systems and type inference\\n\\n-  A code editor or IDE of your choice (we recommend Visual Studio Code or IntelliJ IDEA)\\n\\n**Technologies/Tools Needed**\\n\\n-  TypeScript 4.0 or later\\n\\n-  Node.js 14.0 or later\\n\\n-  A code editor or IDE (as mentioned above)\\n\\n**Links to Tools/ Packages**\\n\\n-  TypeScript: https://www.typescriptlang.org/\\n\\n-  Visual Studio Code: https://code.visualstudio.com/\\n\\n-  IntelliJ IDEA: https://www.jetbrains.com/idea/\\n\\n**Technical Background**\\n\\nTypeScript generics are a powerful feature that allows developers to create reusable code that can work with multiple data types. At its core, a generic type is a type that is parameterized by one or more type parameters. These type parameters are then used to constrain the type of data that can be used with the generic type.\\n\\nWhen working with generics, it’s essential to understand the concept of type inference. Type inference is the process by which the TypeScript compiler determines the type of a generic variable. This is typically done using a combination of type annotations and type constraints.\\n\\n**Core Concepts and Terminology**Best Practices and Optimization**\\n\\nHere are some best practices and optimization techniques for using generics in TypeScript:\\n\\n-  **Use performance-critical code**: Generics can be slower than non-generic code due to the overhead of type inference. Use generics only when necessary.\\n\\n-  **Avoid using generics for simple data structures**: Generics can make data structures more complex and harder to maintain. Use simple data structures when possible.\\n\\n-  **Use interfaces**: Interfaces can help define the shape of your data and improve type safety.\\n\\n-  **Avoid using multiple type parameters**: Multiple type parameters can make your code harder to read and maintain.\\n\\n**Testing and Debugging**\\n\\nHere are some tips for testing and debugging generic code:\\n\\n-  **Use the TypeScript compiler**: The TypeScript compiler can help catch type errors and other issues with your code.\\n\\n-  **Use a testing framework**: A testing framework can help you write tests for your code and ensure that it works correctly.\\n\\n-  **Use debugging tools**: Debugging tools can help you identify issues with your code and fix them.\\n\\n-  **Avoid using console.log**: Console.log can make it harder to debug your code. Use a logging library or a debugger instead.\\n\\n**Conclusion**\\n\\nIn this tutorial, we have covered the basics of TypeScript generics, including core concepts, technical background, implementation guide, code examples, best practices, and optimization techniques. We have also discussed testing and debugging techniques for generic code.\\n\\nBy following the guidelines and best practices outlined in this tutorial, you can write efficient, readable, and maintainable code using TypeScript generics. Remember to use type constraints, avoid using raw types, and use interfaces to define the shape of your data.\\n\\nI hope this tutorial has been helpful in unlocking the power of TypeScript’s generics. With practice and experience, you can master generics and write code that is both efficient and maintainable.\",\"date\":\"2025-02-09\",\"icon\":\"https://kimi-web-img.moonshot.cn/prod-data/icon-cache-img/codezup.com\",\"mime\":\"\",\"site_name\":\"Codez Up\",\"snippet\":\"Best Practices and Optimization\\n\\nHere are some best practices and optimization techniques for using generics in TypeScript:\\n\\n-  Use performance-critical code: Generics can be slower than non-generic code due to the overhead of type inference. Use generics only when necessary.\\n\\n-  Avoid using generics for simple data structures: Generics can make data structures more complex and harder to maintain. Use simple data structures when possible.\\n\\n-  Use interfaces: Interfaces can help define the shape of your data and improve type safety.\\n\\n-  Avoid using multiple type parameters: Multiple type parameters can make your code harder to read and maintain.\\n\\nTesting and Debugging\\n\\nHere are some tips for testing and debugging generic code:\\n\\n-  Use the TypeScript compiler: The TypeScript compiler can help catch type errors and other issues with your code.\\n\\n-  Use a testing framework: A testing framework can help you write tests for your code and ensure that it\",\"title\":\"“Unlocking the Power of TypeScript’s Generics: A Practical Tutorial”\",\"url\":\"https://codezup.com/unlocking-the-power-of-typescripts-generics-a-practical-tutorial/\"},{\"content\":\"## Introduction\\n\\nTypeScript and TypeScript’s Generics: A Hands-On Tutorial on Writing Generic Functions is a comprehensive guide to writing generic functions in TypeScript. This tutorial is designed to help developers understand the basics of generics, how to implement them, and how to use them effectively in their code.\\n\\n### What Readers Will Learn\\n\\n-  The basics of TypeScript and its type system\\n\\n-  How to implement generic functions in TypeScript\\n\\n-  Best practices for writing generic functions\\n\\n-  How to use generics to write reusable and flexible code\\n\\n-  How to optimize and debug generic functions\\n\\n### Prerequisites\\n\\n-  Basic knowledge of TypeScript and its type system\\n\\n-  Familiarity with object-oriented programming concepts\\n\\n### Technologies/Tools Needed\\n\\n-  TypeScript 4.5 or later\\n\\n-  Node.js 14 or later\\n\\n-  Visual Studio Code or other code editor\\n\\n-  TypeScript documentation and type definitions\\n\\n### Relevant Links\\n\\n-  TypeScript documentation: \\u003c https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/ \\u003e\\n\\n-  TypeScript type definitions: \\u003c https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/declaration-mirrors.html \\u003e\\n\\n-  Visual Studio Code: \\u003c https://code.visualstudio.com/ \\u003e\\n\\n## Technical Background\\n\\n### Core Concepts and Terminology\\n\\n-  Type parameters: placeholders for types in generic functions\\n\\n-  Type inference: the process of inferring the types of variables and expressions\\n\\n-  Type guards: functions that narrow the type of a value\\n\\n-  Generic functions: functions that can work with multiple types\\n\\n### How it Works Under the Hood\\n\\n-  When a generic function is called, the type parameters are replaced with the actual types\\n\\n-  The type system checks the types at compile-time to ensure type safety\\n\\n-  The type system also provides type inference, which helps to narrow the type of a value\\n\\n### Best Practices and Common Pitfalls\\n\\n-  Use type parameters to write reusable and flexible code\\n\\n-  Use type guards to narrow the type of a value\\n\\n-  Avoid using type parameters for simple types, such as numbers or strings\\n\\n-  Avoid using type parameters for complex types, such as objects or arrays## Implementation Guide\\n\\n### Step 1: Implementing a Simple Generic Function\\n\\n```\\n\\n// Define a generic function that takes a type parameter\\nfunction identity\\u003cT\\u003e(value: T): T {\\n  // Return the value unchanged\\n  return value;\\n}\\n\\n// Call the function with a string\\nconst result1 = identity(\\\"hello\\\");\\nconsole.log(result1); // Output: \\\"hello\\\"\\n\\n// Call the function with a number\\nconst result2 = identity(42);\\nconsole.log(result2); // Output: 42\\n\\n```\\n\\n### Step 2: Implementing a Generic Function with Type Parameters\\n\\n```\\n\\n// Define a generic function that takes two type parameters\\nfunction add\\u003cT, U\\u003e(a: T, b: U): (T \\u0026 U) {\\n  // Return the sum of the two values\\n  return a + b;\\n}\\n\\n// Call the function with two strings\\nconst result1 = add(\\\"hello\\\", \\\"world\\\");\\nconsole.log(result1); // Output: \\\"helloworld\\\"\\n\\n// Call the function with two numbers\\nconst result2 = add(42, 24);\\nconsole.log(result2); // Output: 66\\n\\n```\\n\\n### Step 3: Implementing a Generic Function with Type Guards\\n\\n```\\n\\n// Define a generic function that takes a type parameter and a type guard\\nfunction isString\\u003cT\\u003e(value: T): value is string {\\n  // Return true if the value is a string\\n  return typeof value === \\\"string\\\";\\n}\\n\\n// Call the function with a string\\nconst result1 = isString(\\\"hello\\\");\\nconsole.log(result1); // Output: true\\n\\n// Call the function with a number\\nconst result2 = isString(42);\\nconsole.log(result2); // Output: false\\n\\n```## Code Examples\\n\\n### Example 1: Implementing a Generic Function for Array Operations\\n\\n```\\n\\n// Define a generic function that takes an array type parameter\\nfunction mapArray\\u003cT\\u003e(array: T[], callback: (value: T) =\\u003e T): T[] {\\n  // Return a new array with the results of the callback function\\n  return array.map(callback);\\n}\\n\\n// Call the function with an array of strings\\nconst result1 = mapArray([\\\"hello\\\", \\\"world\\\"], (value) =\\u003e value.toUpperCase());\\nconsole.log(result1); // Output: [\\\"HELLO\\\", \\\"WORLD\\\"]\\n\\n// Call the function with an array of numbers\\nconst result2 = mapArray([42, 24], (value) =\\u003e value * 2);\\nconsole.log(result2); // Output: [84, 48]\\n\\n```\\n\\n### Example 2: Implementing a Generic Function for Object Operations\\n\\n```\\n\\n// Define a generic function that takes an object type parameter\\nfunction mergeObjects\\u003cT\\u003e(object1: T, object2: T): T {\\n  // Return a new object with the results of the merge\\n  return { ...object1, ...object2 };\\n}\\n\\n// Call the function with two objects\\nconst result1 = mergeObjects({ name: \\\"John\\\", age: 42 }, { occupation: \\\"Developer\\\" });\\nconsole.log(result1); // Output: { name: \\\"John\\\", age: 42, occupation: \\\"Developer\\\" }\\n\\n// Call the function with two objects\\nconst result2 = mergeObjects({ name: \\\"Jane\\\", age: 25 }, { occupation: \\\"Engineer\\\" });\\nconsole.log(result2); // Output: { name: \\\"Jane\\\", age: 25, occupation: \\\"Engineer\\\" }\\n\\n```## Best Practices and Optimization\\n\\n### Performance Considerations\\n\\n-  Use type parameters to write reusable and flexible code\\n\\n-  Avoid using type parameters for simple types, such as numbers or strings\\n\\n-  Use type guards to narrow the type of a value\\n\\n### Security Considerations\\n\\n-  Use type parameters to write secure and type-safe code\\n\\n-  Avoid using type parameters for complex types, such as objects or arrays\\n\\n-  Use type guards to narrow the type of a value\\n\\n### Code Organization Tips\\n\\n-  Use a consistent naming convention for type parameters\\n\\n-  Use a consistent naming convention for type guards\\n\\n-  Use a consistent naming convention for generic functions\\n\\n### Common Mistakes to Avoid\\n\\n-  Using type parameters for simple types, such as numbers or strings\\n\\n-  Using type parameters for complex types, such as objects or arrays\\n\\n-  Not using type guards to narrow the type of a value\\n\\n## Testing and Debugging\\n\\n### Testing the Implementation\\n\\n```\\n\\n// Define a test function for the generic function\\nfunction testIdentity\\u003cT\\u003e(value: T): void {\\n  // Test the generic function with a string\\n  const result1 = identity(value);\\n  console.log(result1); // Output: value\\n\\n  // Test the generic function with a number\\n  const result2 = identity(42);\\n  console.log(result2); // Output: 42\\n}\\n\\n// Call the test function with a string\\ntestIdentity(\\\"hello\\\");\\n\\n// Call the test function with a number\\ntestIdentity(42);\\n\\n```\\n\\n### Debugging the Implementation\\n\\n```\\n\\n// Define a debug function for the generic function\\nfunction debugIdentity\\u003cT\\u003e(value: T): void {\\n  // Use the console.log function to debug the generic function\\n  console.log(value); // Output: value\\n}\\n\\n// Call the debug function with a string\\ndebugIdentity(\\\"hello\\\");\\n\\n// Call the debug function with a number\\ndebugIdentity(42);\\n\\n```## Conclusion\\n\\nIn this tutorial, we have learned how to write generic functions in TypeScript. We have covered the basics of generics, how to implement them, and how to use them effectively in our code. We have also discussed best practices for writing generic functions, performance considerations, security considerations, code organization tips, common mistakes to avoid, testing and debugging techniques.\\n\\n### Next Steps and Further Learning\\n\\n-  Read the TypeScript documentation: \\u003c https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/ \\u003e\\n\\n-  Read the TypeScript type definitions: \\u003c https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/declaration-mirrors.html \\u003e\\n\\n-  Practice writing generic functions in TypeScript\\n\\n-  Learn more about type parameters, type guards, and generic functions in TypeScript\\n\\n### Additional Resources\\n\\n-  TypeScript documentation: \\u003c https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/ \\u003e\\n\\n-  TypeScript type definitions: \\u003c https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/declaration-mirrors.html \\u003e\\n\\n-  Visual Studio Code: \\u003c https://code.visualstudio.com/ \\u003e\\n\\n---\\n\\n\\n### Discover more from Codez Up\\n\\nSubscribe to get the latest posts sent to your email.\",\"date\":\"2025-01-15\",\"icon\":\"https://kimi-web-img.moonshot.cn/prod-data/icon-cache-img/codezup.com\",\"mime\":\"\",\"site_name\":\"Codez Up\",\"snippet\":\" Introduction\\n\\nTypeScript and TypeScript’s Generics: A Hands-On Tutorial on Writing Generic Functions is a comprehensive guide to writing generic functions in TypeScript. This tutorial is designed to help developers understand the basics of generics, how to implement them, and how to use them effectively in their code.\\n\\n What Readers Will Learn\\n\\n-  The basics of TypeScript and its type system\\n\\n-  How to implement generic functions in TypeScript\\n\\n-  Best practices for writing generic functions\\n\\n-  How to use generics to write reusable and flexible code\\n\\n-  How to optimize and debug generic functions\\n\\n Prerequisites\\n\\n-  Basic knowledge of TypeScript and its type system\\n\\n-  Familiarity with object-oriented programming concepts\\n\\n Technologies/Tools Needed\\n\\n-  TypeScript 4.5 or later\\n\\n-  Node.js 14 or later\\n\\n-  Visual Studio Code or other code editor\\n\\n-  TypeScript documentation and type definitions\\n\\n Relevant Links\\n\\n-  TypeScript documentation: \\u003c https://www\",\"title\":\"TypeScript and TypeScript’s Generics: A Hands-On Tutorial on Writing Generic Functions\",\"url\":\"https://codezup.com/typescript-generics-tutorial/\"},{\"content\":\"16 Dec 2024\\n\\nAdvanced\\n\\n6.93K Views\\n\\n7 min read\\n\\n**Generics in TypeScript** are a valuable feature that enables you to write functions, classes, and interfaces that can handle any data type while remaining type-safe. Consider designing a method to handle arrays that can also handle numbers, texts, and even custom objects without having to rewrite the logic for each kind. This is where generics come into play!\\n\\nSo In this TypeScript tutorial, We will gonna see **Generics in TypeScript** including **Example of Generics, Why Use Generics?** etc.\\n\\n## What Are Generics?\\n\\nGenerics allow you to define functions, classes, and interfaces using a placeholder for a type that can be provided later. Instead of designing separate implementations for distinct data types, you can create a single function or class that can handle any type supplied at the time of call. This method encourages code reuse and helps to prevent type mistakes.\\n\\n### Example of Generics\\n\\nLet’s look at a simple example of a generic function. Suppose you want to create a function that returns the first element of an array, regardless of the type of elements it contains:\\n\\n```\\nfunction getFirstElement\\u003cT\\u003e(arr: T[]): T {\\n    return arr[0];\\n}\\n\\nconst numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4];\\nconst firstNumber = getFirstElement(numbers); // returns 1\\n\\nconst strings = [\\\"apple\\\", \\\"banana\\\", \\\"cherry\\\"];\\nconst firstString = getFirstElement(strings); // returns \\\"apple\\\"\\n\\n```\\n\\nIn this example, the function `getFirstElement` uses the generic type `T` as a placeholder for the type of elements in the array. When you call the function with an array of numbers, TypeScript infers that `T` is `number`, and when you call it with an array of strings, `T` is inferred as `string`.\",\"date\":\"2024-12-16\",\"icon\":\"https://kimi-web-img.moonshot.cn/prod-data/icon-cache-img/www.scholarhat.com\",\"mime\":\"\",\"site_name\":\"ScholarHat\",\"snippet\":\"16 Dec 2024\\n\\nAdvanced\\n\\n6.93K Views\\n\\n7 min read\\n\\nGenerics in TypeScript are a valuable feature that enables you to write functions, classes, and interfaces that can handle any data type while remaining type-safe. Consider designing a method to handle arrays that can also handle numbers, texts, and even custom objects without having to rewrite the logic for each kind. This is where generics come into play!\\n\\nSo In this TypeScript tutorial, We will gonna see Generics in TypeScript including Example of Generics, Why Use Generics? etc.\\n\\n What Are Generics?\\n\\nGenerics allow you to define functions, classes, and interfaces using a placeholder for a type that can be provided later. Instead of designing separate implementations for distinct data types, you can create a single function or class that can handle any type supplied at the time of call. This method encourages code reuse and helps to prevent type mistakes.\\n\\n Example of Generics\\n\\nLet’s look at a\",\"title\":\"Generics in TypeScript\",\"url\":\"https://www.scholarhat.com/tutorial/typescript/generics\"},{\"content\":\"## Introduction to TypeScript Generics\\n\\nTypeScript generics allow you to write reusable and generalized forms of functions, classes, and interfaces. In this tutorial, you’re focusing on developing generic functions.\\n\\nIt’ll be easier to explain TypeScript generics through a simple example.\\n\\nSuppose you need to develop a function that returns a random number in an array of numbers.\\n\\nThe following `getRandomNumberElement()` function takes an array of numbers as its parameter and returns a random element from the array:\\n\\n```\\nfunction getRandomNumberElement(items: number[]): number {\\n    let randomIndex = Math.floor(Math.random() * items.length);\\n    return items[randomIndex];\\n}Code language: TypeScript (typescript)\\n```\\n\\nTo get a random element of an array, you need to:\\n\\n-  Find the random index first.\\n\\n-  Get the random element based on the random index.\\n\\nTo find the random index of an array, we use the `Math.random()` that returns a random number between 0 and 1, multiplies by the length of the array, and applies the `Math.floor()` on the result.\\n\\nThe following shows how to use the `getRandomNumberElement()` function:\\n\\n```\\nlet numbers = [1, 5, 7, 4, 2, 9];\\nconsole.log(getRandomNumberElement(numbers));Code language: TypeScript (typescript)\\n```\\n\\nAssuming that you need to get a random element from an array of strings. This time, you may come up with a new function:\\n\\n```\\nfunction getRandomStringElement(items: string[]): string {\\n    let randomIndex = Math.floor(Math.random() * items.length);\\n    return items[randomIndex];\\n}Code language: TypeScript (typescript)\\n```\\n\\nThe logic of the `getRandomStringElement()` function is the same as in the `getRandomNumberElement()` function.\\n\\nThis example shows how to use the `getRandomStringElement()` function:\\n\\n```\\nlet colors = ['red', 'green', 'blue'];\\nconsole.log(getRandomStringElement(colors));Code language: TypeScript (typescript)\\n```\\n\\nLater you may need to get a random element in an array of objects. Creating a new function every time you want to get a random element from a new array type is not scalable.## Generic functions with multiple types\\n\\nThe following illustrates how to develop a generic function with two type variables `U` and `V`:\\n\\n```\\nfunction merge\\u003cU, V\\u003e(obj1: U, obj2: V) {\\n    return {\\n        ...obj1,\\n        ...obj2\\n    };\\n}Code language: JavaScript (javascript)\\n```\\n\\nThe `merge()` function merges two objects with the type `U` and `V`. It combines the properties of the two objects into a single object.\\n\\nType inference infers the returned value of the `merge()` function as an intersection type of `U` and `V`, which is `U \\u0026 V`\\n\\nThe following illustrates how to use the `merge()` function that merges two objects:\\n\\n```\\nlet result = merge(\\n    { name: 'John' },\\n    { jobTitle: 'Frontend Developer' }\\n);\\n\\nconsole.log(result);Code language: JavaScript (javascript)\\n```\\n\\nOutput:\\n\\n```\\n{ name: 'John', jobTitle: 'Frontend Developer' }Code language: CSS (css)\\n```\\n\\n## Benefits of TypeScript generics\\n\\nThe following are the benefits of TypeScript generics:\\n\\n-  Leverage type checks at the compile time.\\n\\n-  Eliminate type castings.\\n\\n-  Allow you to implement generic algorithms.\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\n-  Use TypeScript generics to develop reusable, generalized, and type-safe functions, interfaces, and classes.\\n\\nWas this tutorial helpful ?\",\"date\":\"2024-07-11\",\"icon\":\"https://kimi-web-img.moonshot.cn/prod-data/icon-cache-img/www.typescripttutorial.net\",\"mime\":\"\",\"site_name\":\"TypeScript Tutorial\",\"snippet\":\"If this site saves you hours of work, please whitelist it in your ad blocker ? to support us ?\\n\\nin creating more helpful and free content in the future.\\n\\nSummary: in this tutorial, you’ll learn about TypeScript generics that allow you to use types as formal parameters.\",\"title\":\"TypeScript Generics\",\"url\":\"https://www.typescripttutorial.net/typescript-tutorial/typescript-generics/\"},{\"content\":\"## First time here? Discover what Prismic can do!\\n\\n👋 Meet Prismic, your solution for creating performant websites! Developers, build with your preferred tech stack and deliver a visual page builder to marketers so they can quickly create on-brand pages independently!\\n\\n## Using generics with classes\\n\\nMuch like we have done with interfaces and types, we can pass generics into a class to type methods and return values on the class. Here is an example of just that.\\n\\n```\\n// 👇 Defining our new class with a generic\\nclass ExampleClass\\u003cT\\u003e {\\n\\t// 👇 Initializing a new property with an array of the generic value\\n\\tprivate values: T[] = [];\\n\\n\\t// 👇 Setting the argument for this method to be the generic\\n\\tsetValue(value: T): void {\\n\\t\\tthis.values.push(value);\\n\\t}\\n\\n\\t// 👇 Setting the return value of this method to be an array of the generic\\n\\tgetValues(): T[] {\\n\\t\\treturn this.values;\\n\\t}\\n}\\n\\n// 👇 Using 'number' as the type to replace our generic 'T'\\nconst example = new ExampleClass\\u003cnumber\\u003e();\\n\\n// 👇 We can now only pass in numbers. Any other type will error.\\nexample.setValue(24);\\nexample.setValue(42);\\nconst values = example.getValues();\\n\\nconsole.log(values); // [24, 42]\\n```\\n\\nIn this example, we define a new class that takes in a generic and uses that generic to type the property and methods that exist on it. We then initialize a new instance of that class with the type of number and successfully use the methods on it by passing in number values. However, if we were to pass in a string (or another non-number type) to this instance of the class, it would error as we’ve already told the class that the generic is a number.\",\"date\":\"2023-08-16\",\"icon\":\"https://kimi-web-img.moonshot.cn/prod-data/icon-cache-img/prismic.io\",\"mime\":\"\",\"site_name\":\"Prismic\",\"snippet\":\"Generics are a TypeScript feature that allows us to pass in various types of data and create reusable code to handle different inputs.Read more\",\"title\":\"Understanding TypeScript Generics and How to Use Them\",\"url\":\"https://prismic.io/blog/typescript-generics\"}]}"
          },
